        author: PositionHunter
        text: >-
          @Facaiya Discounted Cash Flow, which probably doesn't help either! It
          basically means for a set period for time you project the future cash
          flows of the company and then discount them to the present date (to
          give you a margin of safety). 


          A reverse DCF, as the name suggests, works in the opposite way and
          tells you what growth is currently priced into the stock and your job
          is to determine whether they can achieve that growth.
        responses: 0
      - date: 2024-09-12T10:05:41.231Z
        author: Facaiya
        text: "@PositionHunter can I ask what is DCF?"
        responses: 0
      - date: 2024-09-12T08:21:13.347Z
        author: PositionHunter
        text: >-
          @IngeniousInvestor I've given a bit of a tip earlier, but the easiest
          way I've found is to order the stocks from 1 to whatever but crucially
          the order is from your best ideas to your worst or the ones you have
          the most conviction in to the least. Then get rid of all the ones you
          no longer want.


          Best way to quickly value something that I've found is to use a
          reverse DCF. You can see what growth is already priced in compare it
          against current growth and see if it makes sense. I've got one I
          regularly give away if you want a copy.
        responses: 0
